otionally hooked into something just because it makes you angry or confirms what you already think. I tell my kids this all the time, even though honestly I'm not always the most organized about following through on everything. The real solution seems pretty simple to me though. If you're gonna use social media, just slow down before you share something. Ask yourself if it makes sense, if the source is legitimate, if maybe someone's trying to manipulate you. Talk to real people face to face about important stuff instead of trusting random posts. I spend my evenings playing chess with my kids or listening to Bach, and you know what? I'm not confused about what's real and what's not. Maybe more people should just step away from their screens and engage with the actual world around them. You don't need some complicated system to deal with fake content. You just need common sense and a willingness to question things before accepting them as truth.","reasoning_summary":"The persona is a 40-year-old self-employed electrician with no social media presence, which is the most critical factor. He has primary school education, is widowed with 4 children, practices Buddhism, and has high extraversion with moderate agreeableness. His lack of social media means he speaks from an outsider's perspective, observing others rather than personal experience. His practical trade background informs his analogies. His Buddhist beliefs contribute to his perspective on clarity and non-attachment. High extraversion suggests a direct, conversational tone. Low conscientiousness means he might not be overly systematic in his advice. His role as a single parent of four gives him concern about youth and social media. The tone should be straightforward, practical, slightly skeptical of social media, drawing on work analogies, and conversational given his high extraversion.","tone":"Direct, conversational, practical, slightly skeptical, grounded in real-world experience","citations":[],"safety_notes